1
00:00:05,914 --> 00:00:12,578
It's really an honor for me to be here today and to talk about the genesis of Another World.

2
00:00:13,478 --> 00:00:19,883
This game was created 20 years ago and at the time I couldn't have imagined

3
00:00:20,723 --> 00:00:22,904
that it would stay in the heart of many.

4
00:00:26,487 --> 00:00:31,790
My objective today is to give you a clear view of the origins of a game,

5
00:00:32,551 --> 00:00:34,752
how things were done and in what order.

6
00:00:35,498 --> 00:00:40,840
how ideas appeared, and very importantly, in what context.

7
00:00:42,041 --> 00:00:44,662
We also consider the periods of doubt

8
00:00:45,762 --> 00:00:48,583
and the obstacles I met along the way.

9
00:00:53,945 --> 00:00:56,446
As curious as it seems, I started

10
00:00:56,486 --> 00:00:59,987
to create the game without knowing what it would be.

11
00:01:01,767 --> 00:01:04,608
The creation of this game was an improvisation.

12
00:01:06,082 --> 00:01:10,163
And that was not clear at the time, but in retrospect,

13
00:01:10,223 --> 00:01:12,864
20 years later, I can see a parallel

14
00:01:13,144 --> 00:01:14,825
with theater improvisation.

15
00:01:16,145 --> 00:01:17,986
Because in theater improvisation,

16
00:01:18,006 --> 00:01:22,127
the actors have to follow predefined rules.

17
00:01:22,947 --> 00:01:26,068
And they must respect them and play along with them.

18
00:01:26,808 --> 00:01:30,149
For another world, I set some very strong constraints,

19
00:01:30,489 --> 00:01:31,629
like using polygons.

20
00:01:33,550 --> 00:01:35,230
And also, in improvisation.

21
00:01:35,928 --> 00:01:42,753
we develop the story layer by layer without knowing where it is going precisely.

22
00:01:43,854 --> 00:01:51,380
That is what happened for Another World. That's why I'd like to present the creative process

23
00:01:51,800 --> 00:01:54,482
chronologically, if that's okay with you.

24
00:02:02,589 --> 00:02:02,689
So

25
00:02:03,904 --> 00:02:08,627
The talk will be like a diary divided in four parts.

26
00:02:09,387 --> 00:02:13,490
First, I will talk about the ignition, the desire that

27
00:02:13,550 --> 00:02:14,711
sparked the development.

28
00:02:15,711 --> 00:02:19,394
Then, we will look at the technology behind the game,

29
00:02:19,754 --> 00:02:23,676
how it shaped the design, and give a solid foundation

30
00:02:23,757 --> 00:02:24,357
to create it.

31
00:02:25,358 --> 00:02:28,680
Then, I will talk about the creation of the game itself,

32
00:02:29,260 --> 00:02:31,442
gameplay, graphics, animation, and story.

33
00:02:32,780 --> 00:02:35,161
than the publishing aspects.

34
00:02:37,101 --> 00:02:39,302
As far as possible, I will describe

35
00:02:39,322 --> 00:02:44,124
the context of the creation and how the flourishing of ideas

36
00:02:44,704 --> 00:02:47,325
is as important as ideas themselves.

37
00:02:52,267 --> 00:02:55,388
First, let's brush on the context.

38
00:02:57,509 --> 00:02:58,749
We are in July 1989.

39
00:02:58,789 --> 00:02:59,469
It is.

40
00:03:02,799 --> 00:03:03,920
the Amiga era.

41
00:03:10,924 --> 00:03:17,467
I'm 22 years old, still living in my parents' house.

42
00:03:18,588 --> 00:03:25,472
Okay, this photo was taken in 1991 at the end of the development, but in 1989, there

43
00:03:25,492 --> 00:03:27,413
would be no less mess, unfortunately.

44
00:03:30,411 --> 00:03:37,995
I had been creating various games since 1983 on various platforms like Oric-One, Amstrad,

45
00:03:38,916 --> 00:03:40,537
and of course, Amiga.

46
00:03:42,197 --> 00:03:48,161
The average time to create this game was from three weeks to six months.

47
00:03:50,862 --> 00:03:52,583
None has been really successful.

48
00:03:55,365 --> 00:04:00,047
And I had just finished creating all the graphics and animation for

49
00:04:00,817 --> 00:04:05,499
Future Wars, which is a game designed by Paul Cuisset.

50
00:04:08,760 --> 00:04:16,243
And Dragon Slayer was just released on Amiga, and its huge animations really impressed me.

51
00:04:16,983 --> 00:04:18,944
I was wondering how to do this.

52
00:04:24,666 --> 00:04:29,888
This game was purely beatmap. It was running on eight floppy disks.

53
00:04:30,710 --> 00:04:33,911
But it inspired me, technically speaking,

54
00:04:34,151 --> 00:04:37,832
to base a 2D game on a polygon drawing technology.

55
00:04:38,532 --> 00:04:39,232
Why polygons?

56
00:04:40,772 --> 00:04:43,333
Polygons mean low memory usage.

57
00:04:43,993 --> 00:04:47,614
And therefore, it can cover a huge part of the screen

58
00:04:47,874 --> 00:04:49,115
with very few data.

59
00:04:50,575 --> 00:04:52,656
It seemed very advantageous.

60
00:04:53,536 --> 00:04:57,557
And I felt it could open new horizons.

61
00:05:03,625 --> 00:05:09,510
Also, a new thing that came with the Amiga was the ability to connect a Genlock.

62
00:05:10,351 --> 00:05:17,636
What's a Genlock? A Genlock is a hardware that enables you to put a video behind the picture,

63
00:05:17,656 --> 00:05:22,600
and the picture which is displayed on the screen, of course.

64
00:05:23,701 --> 00:05:30,006
And I had seen a demo of this in a shop, and this led me to a conclusion that

65
00:05:31,472 --> 00:05:35,915
If I could connect a video camcorder to the Amiga

66
00:05:36,355 --> 00:05:39,777
with this hardware, I could create realistic animation

67
00:05:40,158 --> 00:05:43,019
with polygons by using the classical technique

68
00:05:43,179 --> 00:05:44,000
of rotoscoping.

69
00:05:48,423 --> 00:05:55,767
Well, an idea is an idea, and it needed to become real

70
00:05:55,967 --> 00:05:56,828
to have any value.

71
00:05:58,449 --> 00:05:59,590
But there was.

72
00:06:00,260 --> 00:06:01,360
One crucial question.

73
00:06:02,280 --> 00:06:05,301
Was it possible to draw enough polygons at the right speed?

74
00:06:06,041 --> 00:06:08,922
I hadn't coded for two years.

75
00:06:09,702 --> 00:06:13,584
And my last experience with C language was a disaster.

76
00:06:16,344 --> 00:06:17,745
Yes, I promise.

77
00:06:18,445 --> 00:06:20,646
It was really depressing, almost.

78
00:06:21,346 --> 00:06:26,027
So I chose to code in assembly language, which was familiar

79
00:06:26,087 --> 00:06:26,347
to me.

80
00:06:27,011 --> 00:06:32,895
And I prototyped a routine which drew a few polygons at 60 frames per second.

81
00:06:33,496 --> 00:06:37,859
And I'm strengthening the system that reduced to 20 frames per second.

82
00:06:38,339 --> 00:06:40,181
And that was good enough to go further.

83
00:06:41,021 --> 00:06:48,387
So I decided that the graphics unit would be polygons and polygons only.

84
00:06:49,107 --> 00:06:50,148
That was the constraint.

85
00:06:52,470 --> 00:06:53,711
This was a major...

86
00:06:54,491 --> 00:07:01,473
turning point in the creation of a game. It was like a dogma. I was sure that polygons

87
00:07:01,533 --> 00:07:12,237
were the greatest thing in the world. I was obsessed by these polygons, how this car would

88
00:07:12,317 --> 00:07:24,281
look in polygons, how would a potato look in polygons, and how a quad would look in

89
00:07:25,220 --> 00:07:40,292
in polygon. Well, something's wrong. Where the hell is this? Aha, okay. Pixygon! What's

90
00:07:40,352 --> 00:07:50,220
a pixygon? It's a polygon so small that it has the size of a pixel. I was used to doing

91
00:07:50,280 --> 00:07:52,962
some pixel art, but dealing with flat surfaces.

92
00:07:54,664 --> 00:07:55,504
was something new.

93
00:07:56,645 --> 00:08:00,147
The first time I used polygons to create graphics,

94
00:08:00,687 --> 00:08:07,770
I was spending hours and hours drawing pixels with polygons.

95
00:08:09,011 --> 00:08:10,231
The clock was ticking.

96
00:08:11,492 --> 00:08:14,253
And months later, I was still on the first level.

97
00:08:15,934 --> 00:08:17,094
That was discouraging.

98
00:08:17,575 --> 00:08:19,456
And after coding a third of a game,

99
00:08:19,916 --> 00:08:20,756
I reverted to.

100
00:08:23,399 --> 00:08:26,542
to using some bitmap when I needed details

101
00:08:26,642 --> 00:08:27,602
for some backgrounds.

102
00:08:28,603 --> 00:08:32,546
But finally, the whole game uses only 10 bitmaps.

103
00:08:35,729 --> 00:08:42,134
As you see, this choice brought new obstacles, especially

104
00:08:42,194 --> 00:08:44,236
for detailed backgrounds.

105
00:08:44,596 --> 00:08:47,038
But it opened new horizons for animation.

106
00:08:58,579 --> 00:09:02,660
Again, what I would create, I strictly didn't know.

107
00:09:03,640 --> 00:09:10,122
I can tell you, I tried, and it was a nightmare because it was too difficult to design without

108
00:09:10,182 --> 00:09:12,582
knowing precisely the technical limits.

109
00:09:16,843 --> 00:09:24,045
I just knew that I wanted to create a game with a cinematic feeling on a science fiction

110
00:09:24,405 --> 00:09:26,945
theme with the rhythm of a movie.

111
00:09:27,787 --> 00:09:33,730
but not especially having a story. I mean a well-defined script.

112
00:09:34,571 --> 00:09:45,637
I was thinking more in terms of mood, ambience, movie, but no story. Yes, because it was not the

113
00:09:45,657 --> 00:09:52,382
story side that interested me the most, but the rhythm and the narrative tension which is connected

114
00:09:53,903 --> 00:09:57,345
but different from a story. This is an important point.

115
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:05,266
I could have said, I want to create a game where a scientist is projected into an unknown

116
00:10:05,386 --> 00:10:11,811
universe where he will meet a friend who will help him all along the game and sure, the

117
00:10:12,452 --> 00:10:14,334
hero will have red hair.

118
00:10:15,014 --> 00:10:16,876
And in the end, he will almost die.

119
00:10:17,416 --> 00:10:20,539
But I had no idea of this at the time.

120
00:10:20,699 --> 00:10:21,200
I was stuck.

121
00:10:23,865 --> 00:10:28,927
It drove me to the conclusion that the only way to solve this situation was to produce.

122
00:10:30,147 --> 00:10:34,608
But no specific tools for polygons existed.

123
00:10:35,949 --> 00:10:39,470
And I had to create the whole game system from scratch, too.

124
00:10:41,850 --> 00:10:44,611
Let's see the tools used to create the game.

125
00:10:45,972 --> 00:10:47,012
There are two aspects.

126
00:10:48,132 --> 00:10:51,953
One, a polygon editor to edit all graphics.

127
00:10:53,572 --> 00:10:58,553
And the hover was a homemade editor for the homemade interpreted language.

128
00:10:59,694 --> 00:11:03,315
This interpreted language was used to code all the game logic.

129
00:11:05,296 --> 00:11:13,699
The tool was coded partly in GFA basic and in assembly language. Basic easy to learn was used

130
00:11:14,319 --> 00:11:21,042
to create the user interface since I didn't need performance. The assembly language.

131
00:11:21,707 --> 00:11:34,061
was used only for the core game engine. Let's see the graphic editor. On the bottom are

132
00:11:34,441 --> 00:11:40,628
all the tools. It's possible to create an object, a polygon, add a point, move a point,

133
00:11:40,988 --> 00:11:41,929
change its color.

134
00:11:46,283 --> 00:11:55,305
The idea was to code a tool where every polygon can be grouped together so that it can be

135
00:11:55,425 --> 00:12:02,867
easily manipulated and where each group of polygons can be grouped together again like

136
00:12:03,027 --> 00:12:03,967
Russian dolls.

137
00:12:06,348 --> 00:12:13,830
Here you can see that Lester is made of several polygons, but his head is another group of

138
00:12:13,890 --> 00:12:14,370
polygons.

139
00:12:19,847 --> 00:12:24,589
there was a special color which enabled transparency.

140
00:12:25,669 --> 00:12:28,010
Indeed, that was a color palette trick,

141
00:12:28,570 --> 00:12:32,111
and it is how I added some light effects.

142
00:12:33,851 --> 00:12:35,892
So that's for the graphic side.

143
00:12:37,192 --> 00:12:40,773
And then just by hitting a key, I

144
00:12:40,813 --> 00:12:43,774
was able to switch from the graphic editor

145
00:12:43,834 --> 00:12:45,955
to the code editor, which

146
00:12:46,907 --> 00:12:49,650
which lead us to the specific language of the game.

147
00:12:55,115 --> 00:13:03,342
I made the choice of an interpreted language because in 1985, I designed this for a game

148
00:13:03,382 --> 00:13:04,803
called Infernal Runner.

149
00:13:05,404 --> 00:13:10,929
This was, and this was really much easier to program than in assembly language.

150
00:13:11,429 --> 00:13:13,631
The big advantage is that the game...

151
00:13:14,283 --> 00:13:16,485
would be interpreted in real time,

152
00:13:17,065 --> 00:13:19,908
so no compiling was necessary to run the game.

153
00:13:20,769 --> 00:13:24,852
That was a key feature to be efficient during its creation.

154
00:13:27,615 --> 00:13:31,378
What is more, the connection between the two editors

155
00:13:31,538 --> 00:13:33,080
went even tighter.

156
00:13:34,101 --> 00:13:39,185
What we see on the left is the visualization of a drawing code

157
00:13:39,425 --> 00:13:39,886
on the right.

158
00:13:41,202 --> 00:13:48,628
I could move the graphics and it would modify the code and vice versa.

159
00:14:00,558 --> 00:14:00,839
Ok.

160
00:14:02,220 --> 00:14:07,865
In the graphic editor, it was also possible to run step by step a part of the program.

161
00:14:15,725 --> 00:14:23,351
The key feature is that the interpreted language has a special instruction to slice the code

162
00:14:23,511 --> 00:14:24,452
into time blocks.

163
00:14:28,255 --> 00:14:29,776
It is the break instruction.

164
00:14:29,896 --> 00:14:36,041
You can see the break instruction here, and this instruction pauses the code until the

165
00:14:36,101 --> 00:14:37,142
next game loop.

166
00:14:38,123 --> 00:14:43,287
And the draw function just draws an object from the polygon editor.

167
00:14:45,209 --> 00:14:48,271
This way, the interpreted code itself

168
00:14:48,591 --> 00:14:51,333
became also an animation sequencer.

169
00:14:52,234 --> 00:14:55,356
And it was possible to associate more complex code

170
00:14:55,756 --> 00:14:57,738
to manage all the gameplay interaction.

171
00:15:02,641 --> 00:15:05,683
The language has few instructions, very simple

172
00:15:05,904 --> 00:15:10,547
and minimalism, like the assembly language,

173
00:15:11,147 --> 00:15:12,508
but more readable.

174
00:15:14,322 --> 00:15:18,625
The problem was that no comments were possible.

175
00:15:19,305 --> 00:15:25,589
And the variable name was like V251.

176
00:15:27,731 --> 00:15:31,313
And it carried just a number and no description.

177
00:15:32,113 --> 00:15:35,575
So the solution I used was to note

178
00:15:35,896 --> 00:15:38,897
that each variable was on paper.

179
00:15:40,278 --> 00:15:41,739
And I have a full documentation.

180
00:15:41,759 --> 00:15:43,400
I still have it today.

181
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:46,743
And it works.

182
00:15:51,567 --> 00:15:54,649
So without entering into details,

183
00:15:54,889 --> 00:16:00,354
the engine allowed to run small piece of interpreted code

184
00:16:00,654 --> 00:16:02,556
sequentially on separate tracks.

185
00:16:03,817 --> 00:16:09,582
A little bit like a clip in Flash, but without graphics.

186
00:16:10,663 --> 00:16:11,583
So it was very easy.

187
00:16:12,728 --> 00:16:15,550
to manage timing and sequence inside the code.

188
00:16:17,011 --> 00:16:20,194
Hence, we have one track for character displacement,

189
00:16:20,594 --> 00:16:22,896
one track to manage the pad control,

190
00:16:23,216 --> 00:16:25,698
one track to manage the laser shot.

191
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:31,602
So I had my tools and the game engine.

192
00:16:32,923 --> 00:16:36,726
I learned their limits, like frame rate, number of colors,

193
00:16:37,067 --> 00:16:37,707
memory limits.

194
00:16:39,141 --> 00:16:41,303
And regarding the improvisation process,

195
00:16:41,623 --> 00:16:45,526
I accept these limits as a new constraint.

196
00:16:46,326 --> 00:16:51,750
So now I was not lost, and I can build the game

197
00:16:51,810 --> 00:16:53,892
with these limits in mind.

198
00:16:58,675 --> 00:16:59,496
What's wrong again?

199
00:17:02,278 --> 00:17:02,718
OK.

200
00:17:03,859 --> 00:17:05,360
No common data between levels.

201
00:17:06,541 --> 00:17:07,061
Each time.

202
00:17:07,879 --> 00:17:09,140
I started a new level.

203
00:17:09,160 --> 00:17:16,363
I copied the previous one to keep the basics,

204
00:17:16,963 --> 00:17:21,285
like controls, characters, behavior, and graphics.

205
00:17:22,446 --> 00:17:26,828
And indeed, it was a major failure in the game

206
00:17:26,848 --> 00:17:29,109
development, since for every change

207
00:17:29,449 --> 00:17:34,991
I was making on generic things, I had to do it on all files.

208
00:17:36,427 --> 00:17:40,870
For example, each time Lester's behavior changed,

209
00:17:41,650 --> 00:17:45,753
I had to change it for all five levels.

210
00:17:46,634 --> 00:17:49,296
And later, when I did a lot of tuning,

211
00:17:49,636 --> 00:17:50,977
this became a nightmare.

212
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:58,643
So let's go to the game creation.

213
00:18:03,177 --> 00:18:11,160
The introduction was a landmark because it validated the use of polygons and the use

214
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:12,540
of the interpreted language.

215
00:18:15,121 --> 00:18:17,382
And the whole thing took only 84 kilobytes.

216
00:18:24,597 --> 00:18:33,102
It was a way, so this introduction was a way to explore the dynamic of pictures in a cinematic style,

217
00:18:33,742 --> 00:18:37,024
and especially the transition between cuts.

218
00:18:38,225 --> 00:18:46,749
And also, this was a way to immerse myself in the universe, which was not existing before.

219
00:18:48,150 --> 00:18:51,992
And it was the first layer of the improvisation process.

220
00:18:52,012 --> 00:18:53,553
Hence, the first layer of the improvisation.

221
00:18:54,108 --> 00:18:57,109
I had the first stepping stone for the story.

222
00:19:03,471 --> 00:19:07,172
I had too much belief in rotoscoping.

223
00:19:07,392 --> 00:19:16,475
I created some great scenes with it, but in the end, there are only six scenes that use

224
00:19:16,515 --> 00:19:19,256
the technique, this technique, in the introduction.

225
00:19:19,716 --> 00:19:20,596
And the rest of the game...

226
00:19:20,616 --> 00:19:20,857
I don't know.

227
00:19:21,640 --> 00:19:24,881
In the rest of the game, only the gun sequence and the walk

228
00:19:25,281 --> 00:19:30,243
and run of Lester was made with this technique.

229
00:19:31,964 --> 00:19:35,406
I got the best result from unmade animation,

230
00:19:36,486 --> 00:19:38,287
like the lightning sequence.

231
00:19:40,208 --> 00:19:44,670
Anyway, this confirmed that polygon animation was great,

232
00:19:45,450 --> 00:19:49,012
but rotoscoping itself was, well, a little bit too limited.

233
00:19:59,145 --> 00:20:05,006
The main rule I followed during the creation of a game was to listen to my inner feeling.

234
00:20:06,046 --> 00:20:10,027
What do I feel right now? What does it suggest to me?

235
00:20:11,468 --> 00:20:16,729
That's why doing things in chronological order made things coherent.

236
00:20:18,629 --> 00:20:20,650
At that moment, it was not clear.

237
00:20:21,110 --> 00:20:26,371
But creating a game all alone brought a feeling of loneliness.

238
00:20:27,424 --> 00:20:31,067
which you can also find in the game.

239
00:20:35,109 --> 00:20:38,632
And I was always trying to consider myself

240
00:20:38,832 --> 00:20:41,894
as a player of a game who knew nothing about it.

241
00:20:43,094 --> 00:20:48,558
Each time, I was asking myself, what would I love to experience?

242
00:20:49,439 --> 00:20:54,202
And then, as a creator, how can I surprise and break

243
00:20:55,122 --> 00:20:56,603
my initial expectation?

244
00:20:58,031 --> 00:20:59,994
Surprising the player was important.

245
00:21:00,996 --> 00:21:04,602
Playing with the pacing was a top objective.

246
00:21:33,074 --> 00:21:40,676
the hero just disappeared and from that point I just knew that he would be teleported into

247
00:21:40,976 --> 00:21:52,118
another world. But where? I thought in VR, in Freefall first, but then I thought it would be

248
00:21:52,318 --> 00:21:58,139
much more surprising and unearthly to make him appear underwater.

249
00:22:11,424 --> 00:22:19,507
which gave another stunning moment when he emerged on the surface of a totally unknown place

