00:39:00,325 --> 00:39:00,865
OK.

401
00:39:02,186 --> 00:39:02,726
Publishing.

402
00:39:06,178 --> 00:39:11,061
It was time to see if a publisher would be interested in the game.

403
00:39:11,721 --> 00:39:19,064
I met Delphine Software, who were interested, but I wanted to meet another publisher, which

404
00:39:19,184 --> 00:39:24,086
was in fact the French headquarter of Virgin Games.

405
00:39:26,787 --> 00:39:33,010
Here was a major fork during the creation of the game, the moment where another world

406
00:39:33,630 --> 00:39:35,611
could have changed drastically.

407
00:39:37,468 --> 00:39:44,991
it could have become a point and click.

408
00:39:45,011 --> 00:39:50,294
I love point and click.

409
00:39:50,794 --> 00:39:54,656
And so the editorial director said,

410
00:39:55,276 --> 00:39:59,178
if you want to make it a hit, make it less difficult

411
00:39:59,478 --> 00:40:01,879
by transforming it to a point and click.

412
00:40:02,920 --> 00:40:05,142
So it was the golden era of this kind of game.

413
00:40:05,842 --> 00:40:09,445
And as always, being full of doubt,

414
00:40:10,626 --> 00:40:12,167
he almost convinced me.

415
00:40:12,267 --> 00:40:12,347
So.

416
00:40:26,491 --> 00:40:30,233
Future Wars, the previous game I did, was a point-and-click.

417
00:40:30,754 --> 00:40:32,755
I love point-and-click, as I said.

418
00:40:33,075 --> 00:40:36,177
However, I don't like doing things twice.

419
00:40:37,598 --> 00:40:41,440
And the effort to convert it would have been too huge.

420
00:40:42,521 --> 00:40:46,203
Also, some friends who played the game really loved it.

421
00:40:46,923 --> 00:40:48,344
So I maintained my direction.

422
00:40:53,287 --> 00:40:53,908
And finally.

423
00:40:54,594 --> 00:41:00,800
The game was published by Delphine Software, who were not an international publisher,

424
00:41:01,641 --> 00:41:03,923
but were fully supportive of the creation.

425
00:41:04,904 --> 00:41:11,190
They trusted their game creators and were not intrusive into the design process,

426
00:41:11,630 --> 00:41:15,774
which was rare and extremely valuable.

427
00:41:22,586 --> 00:41:30,491
time to think about the end. How would I conclude the game? I didn't know. And at this point,

428
00:41:31,151 --> 00:41:42,698
I had an agreement for its release in November. I had done three quarters of the game. And

429
00:41:44,559 --> 00:41:50,402
it was, yes, it was really the time to step back and review the game.

430
00:41:50,963 --> 00:41:56,604
the overall passing, how I wanted it to evolve to the end.

431
00:41:59,185 --> 00:42:09,408
So, the idea was to envision the finished game so as to balance the later stage with the rest.

432
00:42:13,669 --> 00:42:18,270
I drew a curve of all major past events.

433
00:42:19,060 --> 00:42:22,503
and activity for the player, and decided

434
00:42:22,563 --> 00:42:27,649
to play with contrasting situations and change

435
00:42:27,689 --> 00:42:34,415
of pace, which lead to the arena scene,

436
00:42:34,716 --> 00:42:42,383
and which lead to an up and down rhythm.

437
00:42:43,344 --> 00:42:43,465
So.

438
00:42:47,788 --> 00:42:54,250
And yes, the cover illustration, I have tales to tell about this.

439
00:42:55,911 --> 00:42:59,351
Throughout my career, cover illustration

440
00:42:59,972 --> 00:43:05,133
has been a major issue and a huge source of disappointment.

441
00:43:05,973 --> 00:43:09,474
I always consider the cover as the continuity of a game.

442
00:43:10,975 --> 00:43:13,735
And it's the first, as it is, the first bond

443
00:43:14,275 --> 00:43:16,296
between it and the player.

444
00:43:17,472 --> 00:43:22,833
the publishers of my previous games had the habit to impose artwork on me.

445
00:43:25,173 --> 00:43:30,435
Like this, or this, or even this.

446
00:43:33,115 --> 00:43:37,936
Well, those games were particularly bad, by the way.

447
00:43:40,177 --> 00:43:44,418
Over the years, I'd become passionate about illustration

448
00:43:44,438 --> 00:43:46,398
to the point that...

449
00:43:47,512 --> 00:43:49,413
I actually wanted to become an illustrator.

450
00:43:52,215 --> 00:43:58,918
So for another world, I didn't want to miss the opportunity of doing it myself.

451
00:44:00,179 --> 00:44:02,941
Being published by Delphine Software was fortunate.

452
00:44:04,321 --> 00:44:06,843
They were fine for me to create the cover illustration.

453
00:44:08,103 --> 00:44:08,824
But doing this...

454
00:44:09,487 --> 00:44:18,009
while creating the game was really difficult as I was already under pressure to finish the game for Christmas.

455
00:44:19,829 --> 00:44:23,650
It took me three weeks, but quite honestly, I didn't have.

456
00:44:33,973 --> 00:44:35,913
One of the big issues...

457
00:44:37,082 --> 00:44:40,922
for the first release in 1991 was the lack of playtest.

458
00:44:42,543 --> 00:44:46,723
Delphine Software were not doing a lot of playtesting

459
00:44:46,763 --> 00:44:47,244
at the time.

460
00:44:47,844 --> 00:44:51,284
And we had only two test sessions.

461
00:44:52,865 --> 00:44:55,245
And that was for the beginning of the game only.

462
00:44:56,925 --> 00:45:01,006
I fixed some major issues, but the game was really unbalanced.

463
00:45:06,700 --> 00:45:15,226
When Interplay became the US publisher, they did a lot of playtesting, and the game underwent

464
00:45:15,486 --> 00:45:16,387
a second polishing.

465
00:45:16,987 --> 00:45:22,211
I fixed a lot of bugs and removed some sources of frustration.

466
00:45:23,272 --> 00:45:31,377
However, they asked me to make the game longer, and some parts became more difficult.

467
00:45:41,185 --> 00:45:41,446
OK.

468
00:45:43,166 --> 00:45:46,328
Interplay wanted to replace the original music used

469
00:45:46,688 --> 00:45:51,051
on the Amiga version with new music for the Super Nintendo.

470
00:45:52,111 --> 00:45:53,152
And I disagreed.

471
00:45:54,272 --> 00:45:57,514
This was a serious source of conflict

472
00:45:58,114 --> 00:46:00,536
as they were doing the porting for the game.

473
00:46:01,156 --> 00:46:04,118
And the situation drove me totally crazy.

474
00:46:05,598 --> 00:46:08,640
The music matched so well the visuals.

475
00:46:09,701 --> 00:46:09,901
This.

476
00:46:10,838 --> 00:46:13,259
led to a big transatlantic fight by fax,

477
00:46:16,720 --> 00:46:17,941
lasting several weeks.

478
00:46:18,961 --> 00:46:22,422
And after exchanging a number of faxes,

479
00:46:22,442 --> 00:46:26,384
I decided I'd use a new strategy.

480
00:46:28,325 --> 00:46:33,367
This consisted in sending an infinite fax.

481
00:46:37,908 --> 00:46:39,429
What an infinite fax.

482
00:46:40,727 --> 00:46:48,272
It's a long strip of paper where the beginning is stuck to the end using an adhesive strip,

483
00:46:50,093 --> 00:47:05,785
such that it loops around the fax machine endlessly.

484
00:47:06,285 --> 00:47:10,248
And of course, I sent it in the dead of night in Los Angeles.

485
00:47:12,344 --> 00:47:20,256
So you could imagine their surprise when they arrived at work in the morning and found reams

486
00:47:20,637 --> 00:47:26,606
of paper repeating the message, the message, keep the original intro music.

487
00:47:42,716 --> 00:47:43,416
This didn't help.

488
00:47:46,478 --> 00:47:53,102
They didn't change their mind until Delphine Software got involved and said that legally

489
00:47:53,802 --> 00:47:58,205
they had no right to impose their choice of music.

490
00:47:59,586 --> 00:48:01,106
And the discussion was closed.

491
00:48:22,960 --> 00:48:26,242
Having a game on console had its own constraints.

492
00:48:27,883 --> 00:48:29,603
One of these was censorship.

493
00:48:30,844 --> 00:48:34,026
Another world could have ended up in a sex shop.

494
00:48:35,327 --> 00:48:38,669
Yes, there is an extremely obscene feature in nudity.

495
00:48:39,229 --> 00:48:40,570
So you get the drift.

496
00:48:41,530 --> 00:48:43,611
The alien women were totally naked.

497
00:48:46,873 --> 00:48:49,375
And here is the cause for concern.

